        "num": 5,
        "type": "reading_multiple_choice",
        "title": "Trip to Scotland",
        "text": "The four of us, my best friend Ruth, my parents and me, were walking over a piece of damp\nmoorland in Scotland. It was my parents' idea to invite Ruth along on the holiday; they'd\nmet her a few times and really liked her, and I suppose they thought it would be nice for\nme to have someone my own age to talk to. I'd been a bit worried about how it would work\nout – whether my parents and Ruth would get on well together – but it seemed to be going\nfine.\n\nWe were on our way to look for red squirrels. Red squirrels are now quite rare in Scotland,\nthough they were once widespread all over Britain. My father is passionate about wildlife,\nand had been researching possible red squirrel locations for weeks before the holiday. He'd\nseen a feature about one particular area in a birdwatching magazine – the price of the\nholiday itself was quite modest – and become determined to take us there. The presence of\nred squirrels had apparently been confirmed only recently, so we had high hopes.\n\nAs we walked, the wet ground made an unpleasant squelch with every step, and the grey mist\nhung around us. Ruth had been surprisingly positive about the whole experience, though I\nknew she wasn't really an outdoor sort of person. She kept saying how fresh the air was and\nhow exciting it was to be somewhere so wild and unspoilt. I had a feeling she was trying\nhard for my parents' sake, and I was grateful for that.\n\nMy father spotted a small bird in the low branches of a tree and immediately became very\nexcited. 'Firecrest!' he whispered, and began to creep slowly towards it, camera raised.\nHe spent about ten minutes trying to get a good shot of it, and I could see how absorbed\nhe was. When I told Ruth later that a firecrest is actually a very ordinary bird that you\ncan see anywhere, she laughed and said she couldn't believe how seriously he took it. But\nthat's my dad – once he's interested in something, nothing else matters.\n\nLater, we did actually see a red squirrel – just briefly, as it ran up a tree and\ndisappeared. My father was almost speechless with joy. My mother, Ruth and I were pleased\ntoo, though perhaps not quite so dramatically. What surprised me was that Ruth seemed\ngenuinely excited. Maybe the outdoors was growing on her. On the way back to the car, she\nand my parents were talking enthusiastically about planning another trip – without even\nasking me if I wanted to come. Which I have to say I thought was very tactless of them.",
